(1) The generating function for $k$-combinations of a set $\{a_{1}, a_{2}, \cdots, a_{n}\}$ is given by:

\begin{align*}
(1 + x_{1} + x_{1}^{2} + \cdots) \cdot (1 + x_{2} + x_{2}^{2} + \cdots) \cdots (1 + x_{n} + x_{n}^{2} + \cdots)
\end{align*}

Expanding this product, we get:

\begin{align*}
\boxed{\frac{1}{(1-x_{1})(1-x_{2}) \cdots (1-x_{n})} = \sum_{k_{1}=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k_{2}=0}^{\infty} \cdots \sum_{k_{n}=0}^{\infty} \frac{k_{1}! k_{2}! \cdots k_{n}!}{k_{1}! k_{2}! \cdots k_{n}!} x_{1}^{k_{1}} x_{2}^{k_{2}} \cdots x_{n}^{k_{n}}}
\end{align*}

This is the generating function for the number of $k$-combinations of a set with $n$ elements.

(2) For the set $\{\infty \cdot a_{1}, \infty \cdot a_{2}, \cdots, \infty \cdot a_{n}\}$, we cannot directly apply the same method since the elements are infinite. However, we can consider this as a limit of the generating function for finite sets as $n \to \infty$. In this case, the generating function is:

\begin{align*}
\boxed{\frac{1}{(1-x_{1})(1-x_{2}) \cdots} = \sum_{k_{1}=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k_{2}=0}^{\infty} \cdots \sum_{k_{n}=0}^{\infty} \cdots}
\end{align*}

This is the generating function for the number of $k$-combinations of an infinite set.

(3) For the set $\{3 \cdot a, 4 \cdot b, 5 \cdot c\}$, we can treat this as a multiset (a set where the order does not matter and elements can have multiplicity) with elements $a, a, a, b, b, b, c, c, c$. The generating function for multisets is given by:

\begin{align*}
(1 + x_{a} + x_{a}^{2} + \cdots)^{3} \cdot (1 + x_{b} + x_{b}^{2} + \cdots)^{2} \cdot (1 + x_{c} + x_{c}^{2} + \cdots)^{3}
\end{align*}

Expanding this product, we get:

\begin{align*}
\boxed{\frac{1}{(\sqrt[3]{1-3x_{a}})^{3} (\sqrt[3]{1-2x_{b}})^{2} (\sqrt[3]{1-3x_{c}})^{3}} = \sum_{k_{a}=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k_{b}=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k_{c}=0}^{\infty} \frac{3^{k_{a}+k_{a}+k_{a}} \cdot 2^{k_{b}+k_{b}} \cdot 3^{k_{c}+k_{c}+k_{c}}}{k_{a}! k_{b}! k_{c}!} x_{a}^{k_{a}} x_{b}^{k_{b}} x_{c}^{k_{c}}}
\end{align*}

This is the generating function for the number of ways to choose $k_{a}$ $a$'s, $k_{b}$ $b$'s, and $k_{c}$ $c$'s from the set $\{3 \cdot a, 4 \cdot b, 5 \cdot c\}$.

